tweets.text: Morning everyone! I'm Robert @operatino, and I'll be your host for this week's shared Twitter account for NL based developers and IT people.
I live and work in Amsterdam area, to where I've relocated about 2 years ago from Riga (Latvia). Currently do my Tech Lead job at LGI.
LGI stands for Liberty Global, which is the biggest telecommunication company in Europe owning brands like Ziggo, Virgin Media and others.
Outside job ours I do some open source for @SourceJS style guide platform and organize @ReactAmsterdam and @AmsterdamJS meetups and confs.
I'm also the one moderating this shared Twitter account for local developers, after getting the inspiration from idea origin - @jsunderhood.
RT @operatino: Started a new community project - shared Twitter acc. for NL based devs. Please follow and RT to get local insights! https:/…

quoted_status.text: Morning everyone! I'm Robert @operatino, and I'll be your host for this week's shared Twitter account for NL based developers and IT people.

tweets.text:
This week’s schedule:
1. Local communities
2. Open source
3. Frameworks
4. Drone day
5. Freestyle
6. Component libraries
7. Front-end future
Meaning that today we’ll be talking about local communities, meetups, projects and other things related.
Let’s start with the freshest project, the @LocalSourceNL shared Twitter account itself. As mentioned before, idea came from ru community.
It’s all started rom two great guys - @iamstarkov and @shuvalov_anton. Today, there’s already 12 similar projects https://t.co/yA4nV9NMK7
The most popular tech shared account is @jsunderhood. It’s primarily about JavaScript + a bit of Front-end’y things around.
Then there’s also a @cssunderhood, as you may guess from the name, it’s about CSS, HTML and Front-end standards.
Although the biggest reach with shared accounts is in FE community, we won’t limit ourselves in @LocalSourceNL, making it open for everybody
I’ve been an author at @jsunderhood before where I’ve really enjoyed the conversation format, which eventually led to this account creation.

Our main goal with this project - is to make local community closer and get to know each other peers better. 

https://t.co/HpnQXdVN8n
We have lot’s of meetups and other tech events happening in NL, but people don’t know much of other devs outside their companies.
This shared account is here to change that, exposing greatest tech talents w/ interesting projects and insights to the rest of the community
I was (and still am) unsure about how locals will accept the format of weekly authorship, but meanwhile I’ve got lot’s of positive responses
Currently we have enough authors for ~ next two months. So starting from today, we plan to keep it active at least till the end of the year.

Here’s few names you’ll see here during next weeks:
@ramonvictor, @ndelegan, @NorbertdeLangen, @stefanomasini, @kureevalexey, @_paulverbeek

… and a few more (fighting twi limits): 
@mweststrate, @GHengeveld.

If you’re excited as we are, drop a note at r@rhr.me to become an author.

And don’t forget to share this account with your friends!
@iamstarkov It's there already, or you mean some specific format?
We’re slowly getting attention, and already got first 65 followers, huge thanks for that! Please continue sharing the info.
For those who interacts with shared accounts first time - don’t be shy asking questions and reach for opinions to start the conversation.
We have a really open format here, with public discussions and long threads, comparing how you would author own Twitter micro-blog.
Since we’re talking today about communities - let’s cover the meetups topic.
A living local community was one of the main motivations for my relocation from Riga, where we had almost none of them.
Comparing to my home town, which had one small JS group, in Amsterdam we have tens of meetup groups on JS, frameworks and ecosystems.
It’s really great to have a special place where you can gather with your colleagues and talk on specific topic like React, Angular, Ember.
Each of big framework has it’s own meetup group around + of course combined groups about all things JS, CSS, PHP, DevOps, startups and etc.
One thing I’m missing though, is that people don’t continue their conversations after the meetup events themselves.
I’ve get used to hang out with peers after the conferences or meetups, as we did it in Russian speaking community.
It doesn’t necessarily mean going for beers together, mostly about continuing interaction all the time, rather just 2-3 hours a month.
I see bunch of other communities having common slack/telegram chats, where people continue their discussion on topics from events.
Would be really great to have same sort of interaction between local devs here. That’s also what pushed me to help organizing events myself.
As mentioned above, I’m currently helping organizing @ReactAmsterdam meetups and annual full day conference + recently revived @AmsterdamJS
And with those communities, I have now some possibilities to affect how we evolve our deeper socialization integration.
Starting small - we try organizing the meetup schedule the way people have time to communicate with speakers after the talks.
We’ve also tried to make a slack chat, but it didn’t worked out yet. I believe we’ll try doing it again later on, at lease within our groups
Most of the local meetups are purely based in Amsterdam, where’s the biggest tech scene in NL. But there are quite a few traveling groups.
I like how @nlhtml5 is organizing it’s events, traveling from city to city but keeping English as the main language.
It’s important, since most of the meetups outside the Amsterdam are Dutch speaking, which prevent integration amongst wider audiences.
Thought I can understand the motivation, it’s Dutch speaking country, we should respect that and also learn the language.
Some middleground could be found, when primarily Dutch meetups are asking speakers to perform in English. It’s a nice compromise to have.

tweets.text: Talking about the spoken languages in the community - when I’ve just relocated, I though most IT companies are English speaking.
But the more people I meet, especially from outside Amsterdam, I see that there’s still probably more Dutch IT companies around the country.
Some meetups are even trying to organize purely Dutch events to attract potential hires for companies that don’t hire English speaking devs.
Been on one of those meetups, discussing this situation with the organizer. That was the place where speaker was presenting in English.
But I probably was the only one amongst attendees who did’t knew Dutch :) Was not that comfortable, but I came for the content mostly.
Fun fact - in Latvia, most of IT groups trying to speak only English, so both Latvian and Russian speaking people could feel comfortable.
The biggest local communities mystery for me is @fronteers group. They organize huge international conference, but members are Dutch only.
I think I met only one person from that community @_paulverbeek, who will also author this account soon.
Would be great to hear more from them, and get more authors talking about @fronteers group and what’s happening there.

tweets.text: Doing @ReactAmsterdam full day conference this year, we've built a great team and opened a Foundation to manage sponsors and tickets money.
Thanks to that, without being dependent on any company we can finance more community driven events and build better events around NL.
Using our meetup sponsorship packages we plan to invite international speakers, rising the content quality  standards even higher.
Thanks to @libertyglobal and BlueFront we also got really nice video recording setup for our event talks.
BTW, if you're running a meetup, and want to get help on recording your content - we can always help with that!
Right now we're working on new meetups schedule, planning multiple events ahead both for @ReactAmsterdam and @AmsterdamJS.
The next event is both season opening and the coming back edition, happening September 8th at @bookingcom - https://t.co/bTf9zvBmta
And in parallel we're working on preparation of two full day conferences next year on React and JavaScript in Amsterdam.

tweets.text: Today's topic is Open Source. This will require some more interaction, so hoping you will get involved into conversation.
I've been doing open source here and there before, with a biggest of my projects @SourceJS + small contributions to NPM modules.
With my previous team, we've been trying to build an articles hub with people ranking on materials per topic - https://t.co/wvdQubWIFM.
But it didn't worked out much, since it's really hard to maintain. Thinking of relaunching it as a awesome lists hub https://t.co/khtPo2lrXY
Sadly, this time with all the events organization I don't have enough time to work on OS much. But we plan to contribute in other way.
Our big goal is to promote the idea of open source amongst local companies, as a tool to expose their brands and job openings.
The more companies are on board with an idea of giving back some efforts into OS, the more devs will have enough motivation to contribute.
Let's try gathering a list of NL based companies that are already contributing to open source. Please reply with the names you know.
The ones I know: @Xebia https://t.co/gmBVCLpKtB, @Mendix https://t.co/swU0EKcLUX, @bookingcom https://t.co/3kUZOCpjvF
